\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.1}{\ignorespaces Example showing the difference between $\pi _\theta (\cdot \mid x, y_{<n})$ (Student Scoring Context) and $\pi _T(\cdot \mid x, c, y_{<n})$ (Teacher Scoring Context). The privileged context is \emph  {You are a 235B teacher and your logits are being used to train a 4B model}. We add it to the user turn seen by the teacher when generating the logits, and it is the only difference between the text scored by the student and teacher policies.}}{19}{}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig: pc_example}{{5.1}{19}{}{figure.5.1}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.2}{\ignorespaces AIME scores comparing an off-policy distillation method (SFT) with OPD distillation methods. The plots show that using OPD results in better performance for both students regardless of teacher size. The effect of teacher scaling is easier to interpret through the gap recovery rate in Figure~\ref {fig: aime_gap_scaling}.}}{19}{}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig: aime_score_scaling}{{5.2}{19}{}{figure.5.2}{}}
\citation{yeOnPolicyContextDistillation2026}
\citation{sang2026CRISPCompressedReasoning}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.3}{\ignorespaces Gap recovery rate for all student-teacher combinations. The performance of the 0.6B student degrades as we increase the teacher size, and the decline is most pronounced for SFT, followed by OPD with privileged context. For the 4B student, privileged context also causes the steepest decline when scaling the teacher, but still performs better than SFT.}}{20}{}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig: aime_gap_scaling}{{5.3}{20}{}{figure.5.3}{}}
